{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523827"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:59:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:59:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13923"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13923"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.07,0.08,0.16,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6542"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65097"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6542"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13923"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50532"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"402"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4049"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13103"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13108"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16652"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65097"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with worsening shortness of breath. He has a history of congenital cardiomyopathy and has been poorly compliant with his heart failure treatment recommendations. He reports ongoing issues with his breathing, specifically that he becomes very short of breath for about a minute at times, followed by periods where he doesn\u0027t feel the need to breathe much at all.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears fluid overloaded with bilateral pitting oedema to the knees. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, and oxygen saturation 94% on room air. Chest auscultation reveals bilateral basal crackles. His jugular venous pressure is elevated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA recent echocardiogram shows severe global left ventricular systolic dysfunction with an ejection fraction of 14%.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this patient\u0027s breathing pattern?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ataxic breathing","Agonal breathing","Biot\u0027s respiration","Kussmaul breathing","Cheyne-Stokes respiration"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s description of alternating periods of hyperpnea (increased depth and rate of breathing) followed by apnea (cessation of breathing) is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003ECheyne-Stokes respiration\u003C/strong\u003E. This breathing pattern is often seen in patients with severe heart failure, as in this case of a young man with congenital cardiomyopathy who has been poorly compliant with treatment. The recent echocardiogram showing an ejection fraction of 14% confirms end-stage heart failure, which is consistent with the development of Cheyne-Stokes respiration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKussmaul breathing\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by deep, rapid breathing often seen in metabolic acidosis, particularly diabetic ketoacidosis. It does not involve periods of apnea and thus does not fit the description provided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiot\u0027s respiration\u003C/strong\u003E consists of groups of quick, shallow inspirations followed by regular or irregular periods of apnea. While this pattern does involve periods of apnea, it lacks the crescendo-decrescendo pattern typical of Cheyne-Stokes respiration. Biot\u0027s respiration is typically associated with damage to the pons or lower midbrain. As brainstem function deteriorates, Biot\u0027s respiration can progress to ataxic breathing, representing worsening neurological status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtaxic breathing\u003C/strong\u003E is a completely irregular, chaotic breathing pattern with random variations in both rate and depth. It represents a more severe form of brainstem dysfunction than Biot\u0027s respiration and often indicates imminent respiratory arrest. While both Biot\u0027s and ataxic breathing indicate brainstem dysfunction, ataxic breathing represents a more severe, terminal pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAgonal breathing\u003C/strong\u003E is a pattern of gasping, labored breathing that occurs as a terminal event just before death. It represents the final respiratory pattern as the brain stem loses function and is incompatible with consciousness, unlike the pattern described in this alert patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECheyne-Stokes respiration in this patient is likely due to his severe heart failure, exacerbated by poor compliance with treatment. The alternating periods of hyperpnea and apnea are thought to be caused by delays in feedback between central and peripheral chemoreceptors due to prolonged circulation time. This breathing pattern, along with the signs of fluid overload and severely reduced ejection fraction, indicates the need for urgent optimization of his heart failure management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cheyne-Stokes respiration is characterized by alternating periods of hyperpnea and apnea, often seen in severe heart failure.","Poor compliance with heart failure treatment can lead to fluid overload and worsening symptoms.","A severely reduced ejection fraction (\u003C 20%) is indicative of end-stage heart failure."],"references":["Brack T, Randerath W, Bloch KE. Cheyne-Stokes Respiration in Patients with Heart Failure: Prevalence, Causes, Consequences and Treatments. Respiration. 2011 Oct 18;83(2):165\u201376.","Cheyne-stokes respiration during wakefulness in patients with chronic heart failure - PubMed [Internet]. [cited 2024 Jul 11]. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27896626/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50532"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13923"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50532"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T14:06:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T14:09:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6542"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65097"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationshi